Steps to Reproduce:
1. HelloWorld::init() ... add the following ... (leave create as it comes from the template)
   auto tileMap1 = TMXTiledMap::create("Tiled/map_1.tmx");
   auto layer1     = tileMap1->getLayer("Kachelebene 1");
   Size  winSize   = Director::getInstance()->getWinSize();
   float scale     = Director::getInstance()->getContentScaleFactor();
   layer1->setPosition(winSize.width / 2 - layer1->getContentSize().width + 
   tileMap1->getTileSize().width / scale / 4 - 2, winSize.height / 2 - layer1->getContentSize().height - 2);
   this->addChild(layer1);

   int x, y;
   auto size = layer1->getLayerSize();

   for (x=0; x<size.width; x++)
   {
       for (y=0; y<size.height; y++)
       {
           auto eventListener = EventListenerTouchOneByOne::create();
           eventListener->onTouchBegan = CC_CALLBACK_2(HelloWorld::onTouchBeganTile, this);
           this->getEventDispatcher()->addEventListenerWithSceneGraphPriority(eventListener, layer1->tileAt(Vec2(x, y)));
           s->initWithFormat("1%d%d", x, y);
           layer1->tileAt(Vec2(x, y))->setName(s->getCString());
       }
   }
2.  add function ...
   bool HelloWorld::onTouchBeganTile(Touch _touch, Event *event)
   {
   auto target = static_cast<Sprite_>(event->getCurrentTarget());
   Point locationInNode = target->convertToNodeSpace(touch->getLocation());
   Size s = target->getContentSize();
   Rect rect = Rect(s.width \* 0.1, s.height \* 0.1, s.width \* 0.8, s.height \* 0.8);

   if (rect.containsPoint(locationInNode))
   {
       target->setOpacity(target->getOpacity() ^ 0xa5);
       return true;
   }
   return true;
   }
3. in the HelloWorld header add ...

   bool onTouchBeganTile(Touch *touch, Event *event);

Now if I didn't miss something here you should be able to click on a tile of the map and it should change its opacity. So far so good.
1. Now add the following to HelloWorld:init() ...

   srand (time(NULL));
   this->setRotation3D(Vec3(rand()%360, rand()%360, rand()%360));

Now the whole thing is 3D rotated after program start. I observed that now my mouse clicks don't switch the opacity of the tile (sprite) which I click. It rather seems to hit the tile that would have been at the location of the click if I never had rotated the layer. Actually my real program has more than one map (layer) and there the behavior is even more complicated when I rotate different maps (layers) under different angles. I may safely say that after rotation the event does not return the click target that I was clicking on ... Hope I didn't do something stupid and waste your time.

